  "body": {
    "export_view": {
      "value": "<p><em>Released\u00a0for 05/02/2017 11:18 CT \u00a0(16:18 UTC)</em></p><h2 id=\"id-1.12.5-Newtextmarkuptool\">New text markup\u00a0tool<br/></h2><p>RepairQ is getting a new text markup tool!\u00a0All of the text markup tools have been replaced with the new version.\u00a0The new tool is more reliable, is easier to copy &amp; paste into, and comes with a few new\u00a0formatting options.\u00a0</p><h2 id=\"id-1.12.5-QpopPairingUpdates\">Qpop\u00a0Pairing\u00a0Updates</h2><p>Qpop pairing is now even more reliable.\u00a0Before this update you could\u00a0break a paired connection by changing the Qpop companion name in your RepairQ settings, but now this will no longer\u00a0cause any problems.</p><h2 id=\"id-1.12.5-QpopLaunchOptimization\">Qpop Launch Optimization</h2><p>Qpop assets have been optimized for faster launch load times.</p><h2 id=\"id-1.12.5-PAXPaymentDeviceUpdates\">PAX Payment Device Updates</h2><p>We fixed an edge-case related to\u00a0a scenario when\u00a0multiple card declines occur - in this scenario\u00a0a sales rep\u00a0could send a request to the device that would cancel in RepairQ, but would not automatically cancel the request on the PAX device. This\u00a0could result in a payment request that is processed on the PAX device, but never returned to RepairQ for saving on the ticket.</p>",
      "representation": "export_view",
